<tr id="L296"><td><a href="#L296">296</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Give it a second. Begin cardiostimulation.</td></tr>

<tr id="L297"><td><a href="#L297">297</a></td><td>JABARA:  His heartbeat is stabilising.</td></tr>

<tr id="L298"><td><a href="#L298">298</a></td><td>BASHIR:  But his lymphatic system is critical. I don't understand it. I shut down the implant. It can't be affecting his blood chemistry anymore, yet toxins are still accumulating in his lymphatic tissues. Computer, display analyses of all biochemical samples taken from the patient in the past thirty-nine hours. Display them by chemical composition. Isolate and display sample number seventeen. Bring up sample twenty three. Sample twenty seven. Sample thirty two. Sample thirty five. Sample forty. Stop. Bring back sample thirty five. Superimpose the molecular structure of this leukocyte with an analogous sample from yesterday. That's it. The molecular structure of Garak's leukocytes has been altered. That must be what's causing the accumulation of toxins in his system.</td></tr>

<tr id="L299"><td><a href="#L299">299</a></td><td>JABARA:  Can we synthesise Cardassian leukocytes?</td></tr>

<tr id="L300"><td><a href="#L300">300</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Probably, but that could take weeks and we don't have that much time. We have three or fours days at most.</td></tr>

<tr id="L301"><td><a href="#L301">301</a></td><td>JABARA:  If we turn the implant back on, we might be able to keep him alive for another week or two.</td></tr>

<tr id="L302"><td><a href="#L302">302</a></td><td>GARAK:  No.</td></tr>

<tr id="L303"><td><a href="#L303">303</a></td><td>BASHIR:  What?</td></tr>

<tr id="L304"><td><a href="#L304">304</a></td><td>GARAK:  I won't allow it. I never want that thing turned on again.</td></tr>

<tr id="L305"><td><a href="#L305">305</a></td><td>BASHIR:  I understand how you feel, but I'm not sure what else I can do for you.</td></tr>

<tr id="L306"><td><a href="#L306">306</a></td><td>GARAK:  You've done enough, Doctor. More than I deserve. There's something you have to know.</td></tr>

<tr id="L307"><td><a href="#L307">307</a></td><td>BASHIR:  What's that?</td></tr>

<tr id="L308"><td><a href="#L308">308</a></td><td>GARAK:  The truth.</td></tr>

<tr id="L309"><td><a href="#L309">309</a></td><td>BASHIR:  I've about given up on learning the truth from you, Garak.</td></tr>

<tr id="L310"><td><a href="#L310">310</a></td><td>GARAK:  Don't give up on me now, Doctor. Patience has its rewards. Now listen carefully. Elim wasn't my aide. He was my friend. We grew up together. We were closer than brothers. For some reason, Enabran Tain took a liking to us. Before long, we were both powerful men in the Obsidian Order. They called us the Sons of Tain. Even the Guls feared us. And then there was a scandal. Someone in the Order was accused of letting some Bajoran prisoners escape. There were constant rumours of who was going to be implicated. Fingers were being pointed at me. By then Tain had retired to the Arawath Colony. He couldn't protect me, so I panicked. I did everything in my power to make sure that Elim was accused instead of me. I altered records, planted evidence, only to discover that he'd beaten me to it.</td></tr>

<tr id="L311"><td><a href="#L311">311</a></td><td>BASHIR:  He betrayed you first?</td></tr>

<tr id="L312"><td><a href="#L312">312</a></td><td>GARAK:  Elim destroyed me. Before I knew what was going on, I was sentenced to exile. And the irony is, I deserved it. Oh, not for the reasons they claimed, but because of what I had tried to do to Elim, my best friend.</td></tr>

<tr id="L313"><td><a href="#L313">313</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Why are you telling me this, Garak?</td></tr>

<tr id="L314"><td><a href="#L314">314</a></td><td>GARAK:  So that you can forgive me. Why else? I need to know that someone forgives me.</td></tr>

<tr id="L315"><td><a href="#L315">315</a></td><td>BASHIR:  I forgive you for whatever it is you did.</td></tr>

<tr id="L316"><td><a href="#L316">316</a></td><td>GARAK:  Thank you, Doctor. That's most kind.</td></tr>

<tr id="L317"><td><a href="#L317">317</a></td><td>BASHIR:  See that he rests comfortably. I'll be back within fifty two hours.</td></tr>

<tr id="L318"><td><a href="#L318">318</a></td><td>JABARA:  Where are you going?</td></tr>

<tr id="L319"><td><a href="#L319">319</a></td><td>BASHIR:  To find the man responsible for this.</td></tr>

<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Tain's home</td></tr>
<tr id="L320"><td><a href="#L320">320</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: A DS9 runabout arrives at a planet and Bashir beams into a house. He starts looking around and is interested in a Cardassian computer console.</td></tr>

<tr id="L321"><td><a href="#L321">321</a></td><td>TAIN:  Doctor Bashir. Welcome. Please make yourself at home.</td></tr>

<tr id="L322"><td><a href="#L322">322</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: After the break</td></tr>

<tr id="L323"><td><a href="#L323">323</a></td><td>TAIN:  Well, Doctor, you've come all this way to see me. Aren't you going to say something?</td></tr>

<tr id="L324"><td><a href="#L324">324</a></td><td>BASHIR:  How did you know my name?</td></tr>

<tr id="L325"><td><a href="#L325">325</a></td><td>TAIN:  Information's my business.</td></tr>

<tr id="L326"><td><a href="#L326">326</a></td><td>BASHIR:  You're Enabran Tain.</td></tr>

<tr id="L327"><td><a href="#L327">327</a></td><td>TAIN:  And you're Doctor Julian Subatoi Bashir. I hope you weren't greeted too rudely upon entering Cardassian space.</td></tr>

<tr id="L328"><td><a href="#L328">328</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Not nearly as rudely as I expected.</td></tr>

<tr id="L329"><td><a href="#L329">329</a></td><td>TAIN:  Good. I alerted them that you'd be coming. The military hates surprises. Still, what you did was very brave. I'm impressed. Can I get you something to drink? Tarkalean tea perhaps?</td></tr>

<tr id="L330"><td><a href="#L330">330</a></td><td>BASHIR:  I always drink Tarkalean tea.</td></tr>

<tr id="L331"><td><a href="#L331">331</a></td><td>TAIN:  A good host knows the needs of his guests. One Tarkalean tea, extra sweet, and a glass of kanar. So, Lieutenant, how's Garak? Has his condition improved at all?</td></tr>

<tr id="L332"><td><a href="#L332">332</a></td><td>BASHIR:  That Cardassian Quark was talking to, Boheeka, I suppose he really did have a reason to fear the Obsidian Order.</td></tr>

<tr id="L333"><td><a href="#L333">333</a></td><td>TAIN:  Everyone has reason to fear the Order.</td></tr>

<tr id="L334"><td><a href="#L334">334</a></td><td>BASHIR:  I don't understand it. Garak told me you were retired.</td></tr>

<tr id="L335"><td><a href="#L335">335</a></td><td>TAIN:  Oh, I am. Have been for years. But I try to keep informed on current events. I bet you could tell me all kinds of things I'd like to know, Doctor.</td></tr>

<tr id="L336"><td><a href="#L336">336</a></td><td>BASHIR:  I'm sure I could. I'll tell you anything you want to know about medicine, biology or tennis. Do you want to hear my opinion on the latest nillimite alloy rackets?</td></tr>

<tr id="L337"><td><a href="#L337">337</a></td><td>TAIN:  I don't think that will be necessary.</td></tr>

<tr id="L338"><td><a href="#L338">338</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Have it your way.</td></tr>

<tr id="L339"><td><a href="#L339">339</a></td><td>TAIN:  Are all the Starfleet Lieutenants as brash as you are?</td></tr>

<tr id="L340"><td><a href="#L340">340</a></td><td>BASHIR:  I couldn't say, though I doubt it.</td></tr>

<tr id="L341"><td><a href="#L341">341</a></td><td>TAIN:  So do I. Tell me, Doctor, how sick is Garak?</td></tr>

<tr id="L342"><td><a href="#L342">342</a></td><td>BASHIR:  He's dying.</td></tr>

<tr id="L343"><td><a href="#L343">343</a></td><td>TAIN:  And you're trying to save him.</td></tr>

<tr id="L344"><td><a href="#L344">344</a></td><td>BASHIR:  That's right.</td></tr>

<tr id="L345"><td><a href="#L345">345</a></td><td>TAIN:  Strange. I thought you were his friend.</td></tr>

<tr id="L346"><td><a href="#L346">346</a></td><td>BASHIR:  I suppose I am.</td></tr>

<tr id="L347"><td><a href="#L347">347</a></td><td>TAIN:  Then you should let him die. After all, for Garak, a life in exile is no life at all.</td></tr>

<tr id="L348"><td><a href="#L348">348</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Say what you will, my job is to keep him alive, and I need your help.</td></tr>

<tr id="L349"><td><a href="#L349">349</a></td><td>TAIN:  My help? What can I do?</td></tr>

<tr id="L350"><td><a href="#L350">350</a></td><td>BASHIR:  The molecular structure of Garak's leukocytes has been disrupted. I need to synthesise replacements in order to stabilise his condition. Unfortunately, my knowledge of Cardassian biochemistry is severely limited.</td></tr>

<tr id="L351"><td><a href="#L351">351</a></td><td>TAIN:  And you think I have access to that kind of information?</td></tr>

<tr id="L352"><td><a href="#L352">352</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Information is your business. Besides, you're the one who ordered him to put that implant put in his head, aren't you?</td></tr>

<tr id="L353"><td><a href="#L353">353</a></td><td>TAIN:  I never had to order Garak to do anything. That's what made him special. So, you're saying if you don't get the information, Garak dies?</td></tr>

<tr id="L354"><td><a href="#L354">354</a></td><td>BASHIR:  That's it.</td></tr>

<tr id="L355"><td><a href="#L355">355</a></td><td>TAIN:  Well, we can't allow that can we? I'll see to it that the necessary data is transferred to your station's computers.</td></tr>

<tr id="L356"><td><a href="#L356">356</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Thank you.</td></tr>

<tr id="L357"><td><a href="#L357">357</a></td><td>TAIN:  Don't thank me. I'm not doing Garak any favours. He doesn't deserve a quick death. On the contrary, I want him to live a long, miserable life. I want him to grow old on that station, surrounded by people who hate him, knowing that he'll never come home again.</td></tr>

<tr id="L358"><td><a href="#L358">358</a></td><td>BASHIR:  What a lovely sentiment.</td></tr>

<tr id="L359"><td><a href="#L359">359</a></td><td>TAIN:  And it's from the heart, I assure you. And now, Doctor, I really think you should be going.</td></tr>

<tr id="L360"><td><a href="#L360">360</a></td><td>BASHIR:  One last thing.</td></tr>

<tr id="L361"><td><a href="#L361">361</a></td><td>TAIN:  Make it brief.</td></tr>

<tr id="L362"><td><a href="#L362">362</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Garak mentioned an old friend of his the other day, a member of the Obsidian Order. I was wondering what happened to him.</td></tr>

<tr id="L363"><td><a href="#L363">363</a></td><td>TAIN:  Did he give you the name of this friend?</td></tr>

<tr id="L364"><td><a href="#L364">364</a></td><td>BASHIR:  He said it was Elim.</td></tr>

<tr id="L365"><td><a href="#L365">365</a></td><td>TAIN:  (chuckling) Elim?</td></tr>

<tr id="L366"><td><a href="#L366">366</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Mind letting me in on the joke?</td></tr>

<tr id="L367"><td><a href="#L367">367</a></td><td>TAIN:  I can see that Garak hasn't changed a bit. Never tells the truth when a lie will do. That man has a rare gift for obfuscation. Doctor, Elim is Garak's first name. Now run along home. And please, tell Garak that I miss him.</td></tr>

<tr id="L368"><td><a href="#L368">368</a></td><td>BASHIR:  I'll be sure to give him the message. Computer, one to beam up. Energise.</td></tr>

<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Replimat</td></tr>
<tr id="L369"><td><a href="#L369">369</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: Bashir is sitting alone, playing with his food.</td></tr>

<tr id="L370"><td><a href="#L370">370</a></td><td>GARAK:  May I join you?</td></tr>

<tr id="L371"><td><a href="#L371">371</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Garak.</td></tr>

<tr id="L372"><td><a href="#L372">372</a></td><td>GARAK:  Thank you.</td></tr>

<tr id="L373"><td><a href="#L373">373</a></td><td>BASHIR:  What are you doing up? You're supposed to be in bed.</td></tr>

<tr id="L374"><td><a href="#L374">374</a></td><td>GARAK:  Out of the question. I couldn't stand being cooped up in that dreadful infirmary for another second. Besides, I feel perfectly fine. So, how's the I'danian spice pudding today?</td></tr>

<tr id="L375"><td><a href="#L375">375</a></td><td>BASHIR:  How's the spice pudding? Is that all you have to say for yourself? How can you just sit there and pretend that the last ten days never happened?</td></tr>

<tr id="L376"><td><a href="#L376">376</a></td><td>GARAK:  I for one, Doctor, am perfectly satisfied with the way things turned out. And I see no need to dwell on what was doubtlessly a difficult time for both of us. By the way, I just had the most interesting conversation with Constable Odo. It seems he's under the impression that I was a member of the Obsidian Order.</td></tr>

<tr id="L377"><td><a href="#L377">377</a></td><td>BASHIR:  What did you tell him?</td></tr>

<tr id="L378"><td><a href="#L378">378</a></td><td>GARAK:  That he was mistaken, of course.</td></tr>

<tr id="L379"><td><a href="#L379">379</a></td><td>BASHIR:  And he believed you?</td></tr>

<tr id="L380"><td><a href="#L380">380</a></td><td>GARAK:  He said something about keeping a closer eye on me in the future. I told him to be my guest, I have nothing to hide. Here. I've brought you something.</td></tr>

<tr id="L381"><td><a href="#L381">381</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: A memory stick</td></tr>

<tr id="L382"><td><a href="#L382">382</a></td><td>BASHIR:  What is it?</td></tr>

<tr id="L383"><td><a href="#L383">383</a></td><td>GARAK:  Meditations on a Crimson Shadow by Preloc.</td></tr>

<tr id="L384"><td><a href="#L384">384</a></td><td>BASHIR:  More Cardassian literature.</td></tr>

<tr id="L385"><td><a href="#L385">385</a></td><td>GARAK:  I think you'll find this one more to your tastes. It takes place in the future during a time when Cardassia and the Klingon Empire are at war.</td></tr>

<tr id="L386"><td><a href="#L386">386</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Who wins?</td></tr>

<tr id="L387"><td><a href="#L387">387</a></td><td>GARAK:  Who do you think?</td></tr>

<tr id="L388"><td><a href="#L388">388</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Never mind, don't tell me. I don't want you to spoil the ending. You know, I still have a lot of questions to ask you about your past.</td></tr>

<tr id="L389"><td><a href="#L389">389</a></td><td>GARAK:  I've given you all the answers I'm capable of.</td></tr>

<tr id="L390"><td><a href="#L390">390</a></td><td>BASHIR:  You gave me answers, all right, but they were all different. What I want to know is of all the stories you told me, which ones were true and which ones weren't?</td></tr>

<tr id="L391"><td><a href="#L391">391</a></td><td>GARAK:  My dear Doctor, they're all true.</td></tr>

<tr id="L392"><td><a href="#L392">392</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Even the lies?</td></tr>

<tr id="L393"><td><a href="#L393">393</a></td><td>GARAK:  Especially the lies.</td></tr>

